The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Valley strife over blast sentence
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                      Valley strife over blast sentence
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	Srinagar, April 23: Violent protests broke out in Srinagar amid a general strike today against the death sentence awarded to two Kashmiri youths by a Delhi court yesterday in the 1996 Lajpat Nagar blasts.        
	JKLF chairman Mohammad Yasin Malik, who led the demonstrations, was detained along with some of his supporters while they were leading a march in the citys Maisuma locality.        
	In some places, youths clashed with security forces and threw stones at them when the troops used tear-gas shells and batons. Malik declared he would go on a hunger strike on Wednesday.              
	 to protest the verdict. We will also go to Delhi to mobilise civil society and human rights groups. A protest will also be organised there, he said before being detained.        
	He urged the Centre to revoke the sentences. The movement against capital punishment is gaining ground across the world. By observing a strike today, Kashmiris have again sent a message to the Indian government that they cannot be silenced by the death sentence. The sentences have to be confirmed by Delhi High Court.        
	The strike, which paralysed life in the Valley, was called by both the moderate and hardline factions of the Hurriyat.         
	Srinagars Nissar Hussain and Mohammad Ali Bhat were given the death sentences, as was a third, Delhis Mohammad Naushad, for their role in the blasts which had killed 13 people. The trio were part of a group of six members, including a woman, of the Jammu Kashmir Islamic Front (JKIF) convicted on April 8. Of the remaining three, one got a life term, while two others, including the woman, were given lighter sentences.                                                                                                                                                          
